VMware Network Types (VMnet) – Quick Summary
1. Bridged Network
The VM acts like a physical computer on the network.
It gets its own IP address from the router/DHCP server.
The VM and the host can communicate with each other.
Other devices on the network can also access the VM.

Easy to remember:

The VM is a separate device on the same network as the host.

2. NAT Network
The VM accesses the network and Internet through the host.
The VM shares the host's public IP address.
The VM can communicate with the host.
Devices outside the NAT network cannot directly access the VM.

Easy to remember:

The VM uses the host as a gateway to access the Internet.

3. Host-Only Network
A private network between the host and the VMs.
No Internet access by default.
The host and VMs can communicate with each other.
VMs on the same Host-Only network can communicate with each other.
External devices cannot access the VMs.

Easy to remember:

An isolated lab network between the host and virtual machines.

